📘 DATA STRUCTURES FOR AUDIO/INFOTAINMENT INTERVIEWS
🎯 Priority: ⭐⭐⭐ = CRITICAL | ⭐⭐ = IMPORTANT | ⭐ = GOOD TO KNOW

====== MOST CRITICAL FOR AUDIO DOMAIN ======

🔥 Circular/Ring Buffer ⭐⭐⭐ MOST IMPORTANT - MUST IMPLEMENT
Used for: audio streaming, producer-consumer audio pipelines
Must know: thread-safe implementation, lock-free variants
Interview favorite: Implement from scratch with read/write pointers

🔥 Queues ⭐⭐⭐ VERY IMPORTANT
Used for: audio command queue, event queue, packet queue
Types: FIFO queue, priority queue, thread-safe queue
Audio use: buffering audio packets, scheduling audio tasks

1. Arrays ⭐⭐⭐
Searching (linear, binary)
Sorting: bubble, insertion, selection (basic understanding)

Used for: audio sample buffers, multi-channel audio data
Bit manipulation: audio format flags, codec registers

2. Linked Lists ⭐⭐⭐ IMPORTANT
Very commonly asked:
Audio use: buffer chains, plugin chain, audio node graphs
Single linked list
Double linked list
Circular linked list
Reverse a linked list
Detect cycle (Floyd’s algorithm)
Insert/delete at positions

3. Stacks & Queues ⭐⭐⭐ VERY IMPORTANT
Array & linked-list implementation
Circular queue ⭐⭐⭐ (audio ring buffer)
Priority queue ⭐⭐ (audio event scheduling)
Thread-safe queue ⭐⭐⭐ (audio command queue)
Lock-free queue ⭐⭐ (real-time audio)
Applications: audio buffer management, effect stack
Audio interviews often ask:
Implement thread-safe circular buffer
Producer-consumer audio pipeline

4. Trees ⭐⭐
(Basic knowledge is enough)
Audio use: audio routing tree, effect chain hierarchy, device tree
Binary tree
Binary search tree
